SIMPLE: polyphonic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Polyphonic
<hw>Pol`y*phon"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/;
<grk>poly`s</grk> many + <?/ sound: cf. F. <ets>polyphone</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Having a multiplicity of sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Characterized by polyphony; <as>as, Assyrian
<ex>polyphonic</ex> characters</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Consisting of several tone series,
or melodic parts, progressing simultaneously according to the laws of
counterpoint; contrapuntal; <as>as, a <ex>polyphonic</ex>
composition</as>; -- opposed to <contr>homophonic</contr>, or
<contr>monodic</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polyphonism</ent>⟦br⟧
